Guide to the Aisling Irish Community Center Oral History Collection
                    <num>AIA.035</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Rebecca Altermatt

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2012-03-28T16:06-0400</date>

unittitle.value: Aisling Irish Community Center Oral History Collection

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: This collection of oral histories and the resulting publication, "When Mem'ry Brings Us Back Again" describe life for newly arrived immigrants in New York City in the 1950s and 1960s. The impetus for the project was a creative writing class run at the Aisling irish Community Center.

p.value:
Published citations should take the following form: 
                <lb/>
                <lb/>Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; 
                <lb/>Archives of Irish America, Tamiment Library 
                <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library 
                <lb/>70 Washington Square South 
                <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

The participants tell of coming to America, the different ships they took, their impressions of New York - the weather, the tall buildings, navigating the subway, electricity and indoor plumbing - their first jobs, their friendships and social activities, and their homesickness. For many, leaving to come to America was also the first time they had ever been out of their hometown. Some came voluntarily; others were chosen or sent by a family member.
When available, duration of interviews is recorded and is included in the container list.
